{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1476"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1476"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.22,0.3,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111982"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1476"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94046"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"6155"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45859"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111982"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old boy presents with a painful left knee after an injury whilst playing soccer a week ago. After he was tackled by another player his knee \u0027twisted\u0027 and his boot studs remained stuck in the ground. He felt a \u0027pop\u0027 and noticed immediate swelling of the affected knee. Since the injury the swelling has subsided however he reports that his knee frequently \u0027get\u0027s caught\u0027 when he tries to extend it and he does not feel stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is mild effusion of the joint, joint line tenderness and McMurray\u0027s sign is positive. An MRI is arranged (Image). Saggital view of image on the left, and coronal view of image on the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures has been damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial meniscus","Lateral meniscus","Anterior cruciate ligament (ACL)","Posterior cruciate ligament (PCL)","Tibial plateau"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMeniscal tears are common injuries in young sporting athletes, but can also be as a result of degeneration in the older population. Mcmurray\u0027s sign can be positive in either medial or lateral meniscal tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial meniscal \u003C/strong\u003Etears are more common than lateral. The mechanism of injury is the same as lateral tears, being a twisting movement with a fixed and planted foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MRI exhibits a torn \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral meniscus\u003C/strong\u003E (the fibular head is visible, which indicates that this injury is on the lateral side of the knee joint) (Image). It is the bucket handle type. Lateral meniscus tears are more frequently associated with acute ACL tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cruciate ligament (ACL) \u003C/strong\u003Etears are most frequently as a result of a non-contact pivoting injury which results in anterior translation of the tibia while the knee is slightly flexed in a valgus position. Patients often report a \u0027popping\u0027 sensation and immediate swelling. Associated meniscus injuries are a frequent occurrence. Anterior laxity and a positive Lachman\u0027s test are frequent positive exam findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior cruciate ligament (PCL) \u003C/strong\u003Etears occur far less frequently than ACL tears. The injury typically occurs from a direct blow to the proximal tibia with a flexed knee or from non-contact hyperflexion with an associated planter flexed foot. The \u0027posterior sag sign\u0027 and posterior laxity are frequent physical examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial plateau \u003C/strong\u003Efractures often result from high-energy trauma in the younger population or low energy falls in the elderly. This type of fracture has been reported to be associated with meniscal injury, ACL injury and vascular compromise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meniscus injuries are very common and most frequently as a result of sporting injury with a twisting movement of the knee","Diagnosis of meniscus tear is confirmed by MRI following positive clinical signs such as joint line tenderness and positive McMurray test"],"references":["Bansal P, Deehan DJ, Gregory RJ. Diagnosing the acutely locked knee. Injury. 2002 Jul;33(6):495-8. doi: 10.1016/s0020-1383(02)00081-5. PMID: 12098545.","Ververidis AN, Verettas DA, Kazakos KJ, Tilkeridis CE, Chatzipapas CN. Meniscal bucket handle tears: a retrospective study of arthroscopy and the relation to MRI. Knee Surg Sports Traumatol Arthrosc. 2006 Apr;14(4):343-9. doi: 10.1007/s00167-005-0678-x. Epub 2005 Sep 15. PMID: 16163557."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94046"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19973"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20447"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19973"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/499003fd-212d-4ba7-b777-1fb1a4629d19.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/stor